{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659272"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:04:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:04:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20861"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20861"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13736"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96483"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13736"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20861"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79125"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"9971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12681"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33061"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96483"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of Th17 cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activation of macrophages to destroy intracellular pathogens","Direct killing of virus-infected cells","Stimulation of B cells to produce IgE antibodies","Suppression of autoimmune responses","Recruitment of neutrophils to combat extracellular pathogens"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of Th17 cells is the \u003Cstrong\u003Erecruitment of neutrophils to combat extracellular pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E. Th17 cells are named for their signature cytokine IL-17, which recruits neutrophils and monocytes to sites of infection. These recruited cells are particularly important for defense against extracellular bacteria and fungi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of macrophages to destroy intracellular pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the primary function of Th1 cells, which secrete interferon-gamma (IFN-\u03b3). IFN-\u03b3 activates macrophages via the classical pathway, enhancing their microbicidal activity against intracellular pathogens.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of B cells to produce IgE antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a function of Th2 cells, which produce IL-4. IL-4 stimulates B cells to undergo class switching to produce IgE, which is important for defense against helminthic parasites.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect killing of virus-infected cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the primary function of CD8+ cytotoxic T lymphocytes (CTLs), not CD4+ Th17 cells. CTLs recognize and destroy cells harboring intracellular pathogens like viruses.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppression of autoimmune responses\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily the function of regulatory T cells (Tregs), not Th17 cells. In fact, Th17 cells are often implicated in promoting certain autoimmune and inflammatory conditions.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe differentiation of na\u00efve CD4+ T cells into these distinct effector subsets (Th1, Th2, Th17) allows the immune system to mount specialized responses tailored to different types of pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CD4+ T cells differentiate into distinct effector subsets (Th1, Th2, Th17) that secrete different cytokines and perform specialized immune functions.","Th1 cells secrete interferon-gamma which activates macrophages to destroy intracellular pathogens.","Th2 cells produce IL-4 and IL-5 which stimulate IgE production and eosinophil activation for defense against parasites.","Th17 cells secrete IL-17 which recruits neutrophils and monocytes to combat extracellular bacteria and fungi."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; pages 200-201."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79125"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20861"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79125"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T17:33:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T17:35:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13736"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96483"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9971"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cell-mediated immunity","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11595"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diseases of the immune system","synonyms":[],"description":nu